        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The Leafs' goaltending clamped down like a vice last night, slamming the door on Calgary 3-1 after a razor-thin 2-1 gut-check over Edmonton the night before &mdash; a <strong>two-game win streak</strong> that snapped their skid and breathed life into a 54-16-11 juggernaut still perched atop the Central Division. At 78 points and 35 games clear of the pack, with clinched status and the No. 1 seed locked, this is no ordinary slump-buster; it's a reminder of Toronto's dominance even amid the L6 fog from Vegas and beyond. William Nylander's been the quiet arsonist, torching nets with 29 goals and 48 assists in 64 games, while John Tavares shoulders 71 points &mdash; the spine holding firm as injuries nipped at the edges. Yet whispers of chaos linger from that wild home finale collapse against Dallas, a microcosm of the rollercoaster. Eyes now turn <strong>Friday's clash with Seattle</strong> &mdash; can they build momentum into the playoffs, or does the Pacific trip expose cracks before the real wars begin?",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
