    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "7-9",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays clawed back from the brink Monday night, turning a grim interleague slog into a pulse-pounding affair that exposed every flaw and fleeting virtue in this 7-9 outfit, now clinging to fourth in the AL East, three games back and nursing a tenuous one-game win streak. <strong>Vladimir Guerrero Jr. erupted for 17 hits in 53 at-bats, one homer, six runs scored and five RBI</strong>, his bat finally thundering when the lineup needed it most in that 9-7 gut-check over the Brewers &mdash; a win that snapped the slide after dropping two of three to the Twins, including an 8-2 thud. But don't kid yourself: this team's still punching below its weight, 11th in the playoff seedings with -1.0 run differential whispering mediocrity. Daulton Varsho, the Wisconsin kid batting leadoff against his home-state crew, sparked early rallies, while the bullpen held firm amid chaos. The real storyline? A blockbuster trade rumor swirling, injecting life into a roster that's felt stale since spring. Tonight, they chase a series split <strong>at the Brewers (6:40 PM ET), where Jacob Misiorowski lurks as Milwaukee's young flamethrower</strong> &mdash; win here, and momentum flickers; fold, and April's regrets pile higher.",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
