    "raptors": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Raptors",
      "league": "NBA",
      "record": "46-36",
      "detail": "3rd in Atlantic Division",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Raptors",
        "body": "The Raptors clung to the edge of the playoff precipice last night, their hearts pounding through overtime as <strong>they gutted out a 112-110 thriller over the Knicks</strong>, a win that snapped a flirtation with disaster and etched their name in the East's unforgiving ledger. At 46-36, they're riding a W1 streak into the fire, holding third in the Atlantic and the no. 5 seed&mdash;five points clear but 14 games back of the division leaders, every possession now a referendum on their grit. Scottie Barnes, that wiry force of nature, erupted for 38 points and 12 boards, his step-back dagger in OT silencing Madison Square Garden and reminding us why Masai Ujiri's rebuild refuses to fade. Immanuel Quickley chipped in 25, but the real storyline simmers beneath: Jakob Poeltl's balky ankle kept him sidelined, forcing a small-ball scramble that exposed their frontcourt thinness. This isn't a dynasty reborn&mdash;it's survival, raw and relentless. <strong>The play-in looms Friday against the Heat</strong>; win, and they're dancing in the first round. Lose, and the summer whispers of rebuild grow louder. Toronto's pulse quickens&mdash;will they seize the chaos or crumble?",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
